The '''fill factor''' of an [[image sensor]] array is the ratio of a pixel's light sensitive area to its total area. For pixels without [[microlens]]es, the fill factor is the ratio of [[photodiode]] area to total pixel area,<ref> {{cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=K5aOhnvGJToC&pg=PA12#v=onepage&q&f=false | page = 12 | title = Image Processing for Embedded Devices: From CFA Data to Image/video Coding |editor1=Sebastiano Battiato |editor2=Arcangelo Ranieri Bruna |editor3=Giuseppe Messina |editor4=Giovanni Puglisi | publisher = Bentham Science Publishers | year = 2010 | isbn = 9781608051700}}</ref> but the use of microlenses increases the ''effective fill factor'', often to nearly 100%, by converging light from the whole pixel area into the photodiode.<ref> {{cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=K5aOhnvGJToC&pg=PA29#v=onepage&q&f=false | page = 29 | title = Image Processing for Embedded Devices: From CFA Data to Image/video Coding |editor1=Sebastiano Battiato |editor2=Arcangelo Ranieri Bruna |editor3=Giuseppe Messina |editor4=Giovanni Puglisi | publisher = Bentham Science Publishers | year = 2010 | isbn = 9781608051700}}</ref>
Another case that reduces the fill factor of an image is, to add additional memory beside each pixel, to achieve global shutter effect on CMOS sensor<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.personal-view.com/talks/discussion/2923/sensors-global-shutter/p1|title=Sensors: Global shutter - Personal View Talks|website=www.personal-view.com|access-date=2017-07-29}}</ref>. [[File:Additional_memory_to_achieve_global_shutter_effect_for_CMOS_sensor.jpg|thumb|Additional memory to achieve global shutter effect for CMOS sensor<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.personal-view.com/talks/discussion/2923/sensors-global-shutter/p1|title=Sensors: Global shutter - Personal View Talks|website=www.personal-view.com|access-date=2017-07-29}}</ref>.]]
