[[File:Parker-Solar-Probe-WISPR.png|thumb|275px|Diagram of WISPR]] The '''Wide-Field Imager for Solar Probe''' ('''WISPR''') is an imaging instrument of the ''[[Parker Solar Probe]]'' mission to the [[Sun]], launched in August 2018.<ref name="svs12927">{{Cite web |url=https://svs.gsfc.nasa.gov/12927 |title=Looking at the Corona with WISPR on Parker Solar Probe |publisher=NASA/Goddard Media Studios |date=16 April 2018 |access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref> Imaging targets include visible light images of the [[corona]], [[solar wind]], shocks, solar ejecta, etc.<ref name="svs12927" /> Development of WISPR was led by the [[U.S. Naval Research Laboratory]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=106691 |title=NRL's Sun Imaging Telescopes Fly on NASA Parker Solar Probe |publisher=U.S. Navy |date=10 August 2018 |access-date=14 September 2018 |id=NNS180810-19}}</ref> The ''Parker Solar Probe'' with WISPR on board was launched by a [[Delta IV Heavy]] on 12 August 2018 from [[Cape Canaveral]], Florida.<ref name=launch>{{Cite web |url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=94 |title=Parker Solar Probe Launches on Historic Journey to Touch the Sun |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory |last1=Brown |first1=Geoffrey |last2=Brown |first2=Dwayne |last3=Fox |first3=Karen |date=12 August 2018 |access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref> WISPR is intended take advantage of the spacecraft's proximity to the Sun by taking [[coronagraph]]-style images of the solar corona and features like coronal streamers, plumes, and [[Coronal mass ejection|mass ejections]].<ref name="nrl20180810">{{cite web |url=https://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=106691 |title=NRL's Sun Imaging Telescopes Fly on NASA Parker Solar Probe |publisher=U.S. Navy/Naval Research Laboratory |date=10 August 2018 |accessdate=7 October 2018 |id=NNS180810-19}}</ref> One of the goals is to better understand the structure of the solar corona near the Sun.<ref name="nrl20180810"/>
WISPR is designed to study the [[electron density]] and velocity structure of the corona.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nrl.navy.mil/ssd/branches/7680/WISPR |title=Wide-Field Imager for Solar Probe Plus (WISPR) |publisher=U.S. Navy/Naval Research Laboratory |access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref> The instrument field of view is planned to extend from 13 to 108 degrees away from the Sun, and does not directly image the Sun; the area of interest is a very wide field extending away from the Sun.<ref name="svs12927" />
WISPR includes two separate telescopes, each with a [[Radiation hardening|radiation-hardened]] [[CMOS]] imager with resolution of 2,000×2,000 pixels.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sri.com/work/projects/wide-field-imager-solar-probe-wispr |title=Wide-Field Imager for Solar Probe (WISPR) |publisher=SRI International |access-date=14 September 2018}}</ref> The CMOS sensors are an [[active pixel sensor]] type of detector.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/content/goddard/parker-solar-probe-instruments |title=Parker Solar Probe Instruments |publisher=NASA |editor-last=Garner |editor-first=Rob |date=12 July 2018 |access-date=7 October 2018}}</ref>
The WISPR [[first light (astronomy)|first light]] image was published in September 2018.<ref name="JHUAPL">{{Cite web |url=http://parkersolarprobe.jhuapl.edu/News-Center/Show-Article.php?articleID=101 |title=Illuminating First Light Data from Parker Solar Probe |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory |first1=Sarah |last1=Frazier |first2=Justyna |last2=Surowiec |date=19 September 2018 |access-date=22 September 2018}}</ref>
==Gallery== [[File:WISPR first light image.png|thumb|400px|left|WISPR first light image. The right portion of the image is from WISPR's inner telescope, which is a 40-degree field of view and begins 58.5 degrees from the Sun's center. The left portion is from the outer telescope, which is a 58-degree field of view and ends about 160 degrees from the Sun.<ref name="JHUAPL"/>]] {{clear}}
